<HL>
   Business Brief -- Healthco International Inc.:
   Countersuit Alleges Gemini
   Violated Proxy Regulations
</HL>
<DATE>
09/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   HLCO
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL SUPPLIES (MDS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Healthco International Inc. said it filed a lawsuit in
federal court in Delaware alleging Gemini Partners L.P.
violated proxy rules in connection with the limited
partnership's consent solicitation to remove Healthco's
board.
   Healthco, a Boston-based dental equipment company, also
said that based on a review of the consents Gemini delivered
to Healthco last week, that Gemini hasn't obtained consents
representing a majority of Healthco's common outstanding.
Last week Gemini, based in New York, said it had received a
majority of consents executed by Healthco shareholders. If
certified, the consents would trigger the removal of the
incumbent Healthco board.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Healthco's lawsuit seeks to have written consents executed
in favor of Gemini's nominees declared invalid and seeks an
injunction against Gemini's consent solicitation.
   Healthco alleges that Gemini violated laws by soliciting
and obtaining written consents prior to dissemination of
materials concerning Healthco's proposed merger with Hicks,
Muse &amp; Co. It also alleges that Gemini is unlawfully
asserting the validity of written consents obtained before
shareholders knew about the proposed merger, in which Hicks
Muse will buy Healthco for $19.25 a share, or about $250
million.
   Last week, Gemini filed suit against Healthco in Delaware
Chancery Court seeking a judgment declaring that Healthco's
current board has been lawfully removed by shareholders and
replaced by Gemini's seven-member slate.
</TEXT>
