<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
09/11/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   OIL PRICES SWUNG WILDLY, dropping in early trading then
climbing on a rumor of Iraqi troop movements near Jordan. The
October crude contract closed up $1.26 at $31.30 a barrel.
The Dow Jones industrials finished 3.96 points lower at
2615.59. Most bond prices also declined, and the dollar edged
higher against most major currencies.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Developer John Portman has missed loan and mortgage
payments and is in emergency meetings with creditors to
restructure the collateral on more than $2 billion of debt.
   ---
   Pennsylvania lawmakers will consider a measure to create a
specialized court system for business litigation, which will
be patterned after the Delaware Court of Chancery.
   ---
   BCE agreed to sell its 48.8% stake in TransCanada
PipeLines for about $1.1 billion. The firm is leaving the
energy business to focus on telecommunications and financial
services.
   ---
   Columbia Savings' plan to sell its junk-bond portfolio was
rejected by federal regulators, increasing the likelihood
that the government will eventually take over the thrift.
   ---
   Cable-television rates for basic service would be
re-regulated under a bill passed by the House. The measure
would also aid new competitors.
   ---
   The S&amp;L cleanup strategy being followed by the government
may have outlived its usefulness, said the head of the U.S.
bailout agency.
   ---
   Duplicating copyrighted software isn't an unrestricted
right for computer users, even if it is for their own use, a
U.S. district judge ruled.
   ---
   A new luxury tax is being considered as Democrats seek to
skew new taxes toward the rich and Republicans resist lifting
income-tax rates.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas will revise its retiree benefit plan,
transferring obligations from a company plan to a
Metropolitan Life annuity. The move will let the aerospace
concern recognize a $234 million third-quarter gain.
   ---
   GM and the UAW are still far apart on job security, the
top issue in their contract talks. However, both sides say
they're optimistic about reaching an agreement before the
Friday night strike deadline.
   ---
   Many hotels will be pressured to install sprinklers in
rooms under a bill passed by Congress. The measure was
heavily opposed by some chains.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices soared Monday, pushing the Nikkei Index
up 1118.83 points to close at 25080.90. But the index gave up
186.60 points during Tuesday morning's session.
   ---
